=https://drugs.ncats.io/drug/GQ8ADD54E1 |website=drugs.ncats.io |accessdate=16 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In other countries, it is used to treat [[cutaneous candidiasis]], [[dermatophytosis]], [[pityriasis versicolor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mims.com/malaysia/drug/info/omoconazole?mtype=generic |website=www.mims.com |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Antifungals}}\n{{Gynecological anti-infectives and antiseptics}}\n\n[[Category:Chloroarenes]]\n[[Category:Phenol ethers]]\n[[Category:Imidazole antifungals]]\n[[Category:Lanosterol 14\u03b1-demethylase inhibitors]]\n\n\n{{dermatologic-drug-stub}}\n{{genito-urinary-drug-stub}}\n{{antimicrobial-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 447916766\n| IUPAC_name = 1-[(''Z'')-2-[2-(4-Chlorophenoxy)ethoxy]-2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-1-methylvinyl]-1''H''-imidazole\n| image = Omoconazole.svg\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| Drugs.com = {{drugs.com|international|omoconazole}}\n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category =  \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = <!-- / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL / P / POM / CD / Class A, B, C -->\n| legal_US = <!-- OTC / Rx-only  / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V -->\n| legal_status =  \n| routes_of_administration =  \n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =  \n| protein_bound =  \n| metabolism =  \n| elimination_half-life =  \n| excretion =  \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number =  \n| ATC_prefix = D01\n| ATC_suffix = AC13\n| ATC_supplemental =   {{ATC|G01|AF16}}\n| PubChem = 3033988\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank =  \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 2298546\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = GQ8ADD54E1\n| KEGG = D08296\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=13 | H=17 | N=2 | O=2 \n| molecular_weight = 423.719 g/mol\n| smiles = Clc3ccc(C(/OCCOc1ccc(Cl)cc1)=C(/n2ccnc2)C)c(Cl)c3\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C20H17Cl3N2O2/c1-14(25-9-8-24-13-25)20(18-7-4-16(22)12-19(18)23)27-11-10-26-17-5-2-15(21)3-6-17/h2-9,12-13H,10-11H2,1H3/b20-14-\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = JMFOSJNGKJCTMJ-ZHZULCJRSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Omoconazole''' is an [[azole]] [[antifungal drug]].\n\nOmonocazole is not available in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web |title=NCATS Inxight: Drugs \u2014 OMOCONAZOLE |url=https://drugs.ncats.io/drug/GQ8ADD54E1 |website=drugs.ncats.io |accessdate=16 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In other countries, it is used to treat [[cutaneous candidiasis]], [[dermatophytosis]], [[pityriasis versicolor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mims.com/malaysia/drug/info/omoconazole?mtype=generic |website=www.mims.com |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Antifungals}}\n{{Gynecological anti-infectives and antiseptics}}\n\n[[Category:Chloroarenes]]\n[[Category:Phenol ethers]]\n[[Category:Imidazole antifungals]]\n[[Category:Lanosterol 14\u03b1-demethylase inhibitors]]\n\n\n{{dermatologic-drug-stub}}\n{{genito-urinary-drug-stub}}\n{{antimicrobial-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added CAS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omoconazole"}
{"title_page": "Micromobility", "text_new": "{{short description|Modes of transport involving very light vehicles}}\n[[File:Jersey Gardens Mall 24 - Segway.jpg|thumb|right|Micromobility vehicles on display in a mall shopfront]]\n\n'''Micromobility''' refers to a range of small, lightweight devices operating at speeds typically below 25 km/h (15mph) and is ideal for trips up to 10km. Micromobility devices include [[Bicycle|bicycles]], [[Motorized_scooter#Electric|electric scooters]], [[Electric skateboard|electric skateboards]], [[Bicycle-sharing system|shared bicycles]], and electric pedal assisted ([[pedelec]]) bicycles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itdp.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/ITDP_The-Electric-Assist_-Leveraging-E-bikes-and-E-scooters-for-More-Livable-Cities.pdf|title=The Electric Assist: Leveraging E-bikes and E-scooters for More Livable Cities|last=Institute for Transportation and Development Policy|first=|date=2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nInitial definitions set the primary condition for inclusion in the category of micromobility to be a [[Gross vehicle weight rating|gross vehicle weight]] of less than 500 kg<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dediu |first1=Horace |title=The Micromobility Definition |url=https://micromobility.io/blog/2019/2/23/the-micromobility-definition |website=micromobility.io |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>. However, the definition has evolved to exclude devices with [[Internal combustion engine|internal combustion engines]] and those with top speeds above 45 km/h.\n\nThe term evokes a transition similar to that of [[Microcomputer|microcomputing]] where the miniaturization of transport modes for short journeys parallels the miniaturization of microcomputers for personal use. The term was coined by business and technology analyst [[Horace Dediu]], in a speech he delivered in 2017 at the Micromobility Summit in the Techfestival event in Copenhagen<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techfestival.co/event/micromobility-summit/|title=Micromobility Summit}}</ref>.\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\n[[File:Kaposv\u00e1ri Tekerg\u0151 2.JPG|thumb|right|A dock of shared bicycles and an electric scooter]]\n\nMicromobility devices can be human-powered or electric, and can be privately-owned or available through a [[Bicycle-sharing system|shared fleet]]. Most micromobility devices are considered to be low-speed (top speed of 25 km/h), but devices can have speeds up to 45km/h and still be considered micromobility. Some speed pedelec and electric kick scooter models fall into this moderate speed subcategory.\n\nAny vehicle with an internal combustion engine cannot be defined as micromobility. Devices with top speeds above 45km/h can also not be defined as micromobility.\n\n== The rise of micromobility ==\nOriginal forms of micromobility, like bicycles and skateboards, have been around for centuries, however their use as a utilitarian [[Utility cycling|urban transport]] mode (as opposed to for recreation or sport) has been relatively low in comparison to trips made by private vehicles outside of a handful of cities in China, [[Cycling in the Netherlands|the Netherlands]], and [[Cycling in Denmark|Denmark]].\n\nWhile micromobility vehicles have long been available for users to purchase, it was the [[Servitization of products business model|servitization]] of these modes of transportation--enabling users to use the nearest micromobility vehicle without having to purchase or store it, and facilitating the flexibility of one-way trips--that led to unprecedented growth<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/11/lime-bird-spin-why-scooter-start-ups-are-suddenly-worth-billions.html|title=Lime, Bird, Spin: Why scooter start-ups are suddenly worth billions|date=2018-07-13}}</ref> in areas where it was available. The rise of the sharing economy resulted in a massive increase in access to micromobility in many cities, first with the introduction of public bikeshare systems, and then with privately funded and operated [[Bicycle-sharing system#Dockless%20bikes|dockless]] bikeshare and electric kick scooter (e-scooter) fleets. \u00a0Most early bikeshare services specified locations, or [[Bicycle-sharing system|docks]], where vehicles needed to be picked up and left. \n\nThe fourth generation of [[Bicycle-sharing system#Dockless%20bikes|bicycle sharing services]] employed a [[Bicycle-sharing system#Dockless%20bikes|dockless]] model which allows users to end their trip and leave the shared micromobility device anywhere or within a [[Geo-fence|geo-fenced]] area. Dockless bikeshare first took off in Chinese megacities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5218323/china-bicycles-sharing-economy/|title=China's Bike-Sharing Fever Has Reached Saturation Point}}</ref>, and although it began with traditional, non-electric bicycles, it served as the template for what would be possible with electric-poweredally-powered and motorized bicycles, scooters, and other form factors. The availability of relatively inexpensive batteries, displays and GPS receivers, enabled by the smartphone supply chains, provided easily accessible components to facilitate for dockless services worldwide.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Belton|first1=Padraig|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-44066083|title=How cheap dockless hire bikes are flooding the world|date=2018-05-15|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> Outside of Chinese cities, non-electric dockless bikeshare has largely disappeared, with many companies pivoting from bicycles to electric kick scooters in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bicycling.com/news/a26623484/lime-bikes-scooters/|title=Why Are Bike Share Companies Pivoting to E-Scooters?|last=Vuocolo|first=Alex|date=2019-03-04|website=Bicycling|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nShared electric kick scooters are considered to have one of the most rapid adoption rates in transport, nearly 4% in one year. Comparatively, it took bikeshare eight years to reach 13% adoption, and [[Carsharing|carshare]] 18 years to reach 16% in major United States cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/populus-ai/the-micro-mobility-revolution-95e396db3754|title=The Micro-Mobility Revolution|last=Clewlow|first=Regina|date=2018-08-06|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n== Popularity and reception ==\nThe speed of micromobility diffusion has not come without growing pains. Some cities were caught off guard with the sudden influx of shared dockless vehicles, especially after companies launched their fleets without municipal approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-dockless-bike-scooter-regulations-20180804-story.html|title=Dockless bike, scooter firms clash with U.S. cities over regulations|last=Lazo|first=Luz|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In 2018, [[Seattle]] became the first US city to establish a permanent regulatory permit requiring shared dockless vehicle operators to meet certain requirements in order to provide service in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://learn.sharedusemobilitycenter.org/casestudy/seattle-bikeshare-program-permit-process/|title=Seattle Bikeshare Program & Permit Process|website=MOD Learning Center|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Many other cities followed suit, drafting regulatory frameworks that would permit these services and more seamlessly integrate them with existing transportation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/420947-growing-use-of-e-scooters-reflects-increasing-demand-for-micro-mobility-says|title=Growing use of e-scooters reflects increasing demand for micro-mobility, says tech CEO|last=Manchester|first=Julia|date=2018-12-12|newspaper=[[TheHill]]|language=en|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref> \n\nOperators, users and municipalities are moving toward an equilibrium where the benefits of micromobility have become apparent.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feasley|first=Levi Tillemann ,Lassor|url=https://www.wired.com/story/e-scooter-micromobility-infographics-cost-emissions/|title=Forget the Car. E-Scooters Could Save The City|date=2018-12-07|work=Wired|access-date=2019-01-18|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> Micromobility users have reported replacing between one-quarter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.li.me/hubfs/Assets/LIME_ENG_Paris%20Sustainability%20Report_11OCT2019_RGB.pdf|title=Lime for a Sustainable Paris|last=Lime|first=|date=October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> and one-third<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/709719|title=2018 E-Scooter Findings Report|last=Portland Bureau of Transportation|first=|date=2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> of car trips with micromobility, and many users report being able to take trips they otherwise would not or could not have made if micromobility options were not available. The potential for micromobility to replace automobile trips, coupled with financial opportunities presented by the massive injection of [[Venture capital financing|venture capital]] into the industry, has led to global automakers such as [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] and [[General Motors]] to invest in micromobility services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/12/07/micromobility-101-for-investors.aspx|title=Micromobility 101 for Investors -|last=Rosevear|first=John|date=2018-12-07|website=[[The Motley Fool]]|language=en|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n\nHowever, data shows that micromobility users also replace [[Public transport|public transit]] (notably, bus) and walking trips. Concerns have also been raised about the [[Life-cycle assessment|life-cycle emissions]] of electric micromobility modes such as e-scooters<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moreau|first=H\u00e9lie|last2=de Jamblinne de Meux|first2=Lo\u00efc|last3=Zeller|first3=Vanessa|last4=D\u2019Ans|first4=Pierre|last5=Ruwet|first5=Coline|last6=Achten|first6=Wouter M. J.|date=January 2020|title=Dockless E-Scooter: A Green Solution for Mobility? Comparative Case Study between Dockless E-Scooters, Displaced Transport, and Personal E-Scooters|url=https://www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/12/5/1803|journal=Sustainability|language=en|volume=12|issue=5|pages=1803|doi=10.3390/su12051803|via=}}</ref>, as well as the long-term financial viability of micromobility companies given minimal differences between product offerings and operating costs in the hundreds of millions of [[United States dollar|US dollars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citylab.com/transportation/2020/01/electric-scooter-industry-safety-design-micromobility/605179/|title=4 Predictions for the Electric Scooter Industry|last=Bliss|first=Laura|website=CityLab|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Classification ==\nWithin the [[Vehicle category|EU vehicle categorization]] micromobility vehicles fall under the L category, and are excluded from the M, N, O and higher categories.\n\nDevices that fall within the definition of micromobility are typically classified as bicycles and are permitted to use [[Cycling infrastructure|bicycle infrastructure]] such as protected bicycle lanes, cycle tracks, cycle highways, and off-street trails. Classification as bicycles also means that users of personal micromobility modes are not required to register them, pay [[Motor vehicle registration|vehicle registration]] fees, or maintain [[liability insurance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/carltonreid/2019/01/22/eu-electric-bike-riders-will-not-need-compulsory-insurance-decides-european-parliament/|title=EU Electric Bike Riders Will Not Need Compulsory Insurance Decides European Parliament|last=Reid|first=Carlton|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wsd-pfb-sparkinfluence.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/2020/03/E-Bike-Law-Primer-Jan-2020-2.pdf|title=E-Bike Law Primer|last=|first=|date=April 2018|website=People for Bikes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Top 10 United States cities for micromobility potential==\nAccording to [[INRIX]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/12/breaking-news/study-ranks-honolulu-tops-in-micromobility-potential/| title=Study ranks Honolulu tops in micromobility potential| last=Wu| first=Nina| work=[[Star-Advertiser]]| location=[[Honolulu]]| date=2019-09-12| access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://inrix.com/press-releases/micromobility-study-us-2019/| title=Shared Bikes and Scooters Could Replace Nearly 50 Percent of Downtown Vehicle Trips: New INRIX Research ranks the top U.S., U.K. and German cities where micromobility has the most potential| work=[[INRIX]]| location=[[Kirkland, Washington]] |date=2019-09-09| access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> the following United States cities had the highest micromobility potential in 2019: \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Rank!!City\n|-\n| 1 ||  [[Honolulu]]\n|-\n| 2 ||  [[New Orleans]]\n|-\n| 3 ||  [[Nashville]]\n|-\n| 4 ||  [[Chicago]]\n|-\n| 5 ||  [[Charlotte]]\n|-\n| 6 ||  [[New York City]]\n|-\n| 7 ||  [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n|-\n| 8 ||  [[Pittsburgh]]\n|-\n| 9 ||  [[Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 10 ||  [[San Francisco]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Modes of Public Transport}}\n\n{{transport-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Bicycle sharing]]\n[[Category:Scooter sharing]]\n[[Category:Sharing economy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Modes of transport involving very light vehicles}}\n[[File:Jersey Gardens Mall 24 - Segway.jpg|thumb|right|Micromobility vehicles on display in a mall shopfront]]\n\n'''Micromobility''' refers to a range of small, lightweight devices operating at speeds typically below 25 km/h (15mph) and is ideal for trips up to 10km. Micromobility devices include [[Bicycle|bicycles]], [[Motorized_scooter#Electric|electric scooters]], [[Electric skateboard|electric skateboards]], [[Bicycle-sharing system|shared bicycles]], and electric pedal assisted ([[pedelec]]) bicycles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itdp.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/ITDP_The-Electric-Assist_-Leveraging-E-bikes-and-E-scooters-for-More-Livable-Cities.pdf|title=The Electric Assist: Leveraging E-bikes and E-scooters for More Livable Cities|last=Institute for Transportation and Development Policy|first=|date=2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nInitial definitions set the primary condition for inclusion in the category of micromobility to be a [[Gross vehicle weight rating|gross vehicle weight]] of less than 500 kg<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dediu |first1=Horace |title=The Micromobility Definition |url=https://micromobility.io/blog/2019/2/23/the-micromobility-definition |website=micromobility.io |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>. However, the definition has evolved to exclude devices with [[Internal combustion engine|internal combustion engines]] and those with top speeds above 45 km/h.\n\nThe term evokes a transition similar to that of [[Microcomputer|microcomputing]] where the miniaturization of transport modes for short journeys parallels the miniaturization of microcomputers for personal use. The term was coined by business and technology analyst [[Horace Dediu]], in a speech he delivered in 2017 at the Micromobility Summit in the Techfestival event in Copenhagen<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techfestival.co/event/micromobility-summit/|title=Micromobility Summit}}</ref>.\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\n[[File:Kaposv\u00e1ri Tekerg\u0151 2.JPG|thumb|right|A dock of shared bicycles and an electric scooter]]\n\nMicromobility devices can be human-powered or electric, and can be privately-owned or available through a [[Bicycle-sharing system|shared fleet]]. Most micromobility devices are considered to be low-speed (top speed of 25 km/h), but devices can have speeds up to 45km/h and still be considered micromobility. Some speed pedelec and electric kick scooter models fall into this moderate speed subcategory.\n\nAny vehicle with an internal combustion engine cannot be defined as micromobility. Devices with top speeds above 45km/h can also not be defined as micromobility.\n\n== The rise of micromobility ==\nOriginal forms of micromobility, like bicycles and skateboards, have been around for centuries, however their use as a utilitarian [[Utility cycling|urban transport]] mode (as opposed to for recreation or sport) has been relatively low in comparison to trips made by private vehicles outside of a handful of cities in China, [[Cycling in the Netherlands|the Netherlands]], and [[Cycling in Denmark|Denmark]].\n\nWhile micromobility vehicles have long been available for users to purchase, it was the [[Servitization of products business model|servitization]] of these modes of transportation--enabling users to use the nearest micromobility vehicle without having to purchase or store it, and facilitating the flexibility of one-way trips--that led to unprecedented growth<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/11/lime-bird-spin-why-scooter-start-ups-are-suddenly-worth-billions.html|title=Lime, Bird, Spin: Why scooter start-ups are suddenly worth billions|date=2018-07-13}}</ref> in areas where it was available. The rise of the sharing economy resulted in a massive increase in access to micromobility in many cities, first with the introduction of public bikeshare systems, and then with privately funded and operated [[Bicycle-sharing system#Dockless%20bikes|dockless]] bikeshare and electric kick scooter (e-scooter) fleets. \u00a0Most early bikeshare services specified locations, or [[Bicycle-sharing system|docks]], where vehicles needed to be picked up and left. \n\nThe fourth generation of [[Bicycle-sharing system#Dockless%20bikes|bicycle sharing services]] employed a [[Bicycle-sharing system#Dockless%20bikes|dockless]] model which allows users to end their trip and leave the shared micromobility device anywhere or within a [[Geo-fence|geo-fenced]] area. Dockless bikeshare first took off in Chinese megacities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5218323/china-bicycles-sharing-economy/|title=China's Bike-Sharing Fever Has Reached Saturation Point}}</ref>, and although it began with traditional, non-electric bicycles, it served as the template for what would be possible with electric-poweredally-powered and motorized bicycles, scooters, and other form factors. The availability of relatively inexpensive batteries, displays and GPS receivers, enabled by the smartphone supply chains, provided easily accessible components to facilitate for dockless services worldwide.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Belton|first1=Padraig|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-44066083|title=How cheap dockless hire bikes are flooding the world|date=2018-05-15|newspaper=BBC News}}</ref> Outside of Chinese cities, non-electric dockless bikeshare has largely disappeared, with many companies pivoting from bicycles to electric kick scooters in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bicycling.com/news/a26623484/lime-bikes-scooters/|title=Why Are Bike Share Companies Pivoting to E-Scooters?|last=Vuocolo|first=Alex|date=2019-03-04|website=Bicycling|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nShared electric kick scooters are considered to have one of the most rapid adoption rates in transport, nearly 4% in one year. Comparatively, it took bikeshare eight years to reach 13% adoption, and [[Carsharing|carshare]] 18 years to reach 16% in major United States cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/populus-ai/the-micro-mobility-revolution-95e396db3754|title=The Micro-Mobility Revolution|last=Clewlow|first=Regina|date=2018-08-06|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n== Popularity and reception ==\nThe speed of micromobility diffusion has not come without growing pains. Some cities were caught off guard with the sudden influx of shared dockless vehicles, especially after companies launched their fleets without municipal approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-dockless-bike-scooter-regulations-20180804-story.html|title=Dockless bike, scooter firms clash with U.S. cities over regulations|last=Lazo|first=Luz|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In 2018, [[Seattle]] became the first US city to establish a permanent regulatory permit requiring shared dockless vehicle operators to meet certain requirements in order to provide service in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://learn.sharedusemobilitycenter.org/casestudy/seattle-bikeshare-program-permit-process/|title=Seattle Bikeshare Program & Permit Process|website=MOD Learning Center|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Many other cities followed suit, drafting regulatory frameworks that would permit these services and more seamlessly integrate them with existing transportation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/420947-growing-use-of-e-scooters-reflects-increasing-demand-for-micro-mobility-says|title=Growing use of e-scooters reflects increasing demand for micro-mobility, says tech CEO|last=Manchester|first=Julia|date=2018-12-12|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref> \n\nOperators, users and municipalities are moving toward an equilibrium where the benefits of micromobility have become apparent.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feasley|first=Levi Tillemann ,Lassor|url=https://www.wired.com/story/e-scooter-micromobility-infographics-cost-emissions/|title=Forget the Car. E-Scooters Could Save The City|date=2018-12-07|work=Wired|access-date=2019-01-18|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> Micromobility users have reported replacing between one-quarter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.li.me/hubfs/Assets/LIME_ENG_Paris%20Sustainability%20Report_11OCT2019_RGB.pdf|title=Lime for a Sustainable Paris|last=Lime|first=|date=October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> and one-third<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/transportation/article/709719|title=2018 E-Scooter Findings Report|last=Portland Bureau of Transportation|first=|date=2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> of car trips with micromobility, and many users report being able to take trips they otherwise would not or could not have made if micromobility options were not available. The potential for micromobility to replace automobile trips, coupled with financial opportunities presented by the massive injection of [[Venture capital financing|venture capital]] into the industry, has led to global automakers such as [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] and [[General Motors]] to invest in micromobility services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/12/07/micromobility-101-for-investors.aspx|title=Micromobility 101 for Investors -|last=Rosevear|first=John|date=2018-12-07|website=The Motley Fool|language=en|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n\nHowever, data shows that micromobility users also replace [[Public transport|public transit]] (notably, bus) and walking trips. Concerns have also been raised about the [[Life-cycle assessment|life-cycle emissions]] of electric micromobility modes such as e-scooters<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moreau|first=H\u00e9lie|last2=de Jamblinne de Meux|first2=Lo\u00efc|last3=Zeller|first3=Vanessa|last4=D\u2019Ans|first4=Pierre|last5=Ruwet|first5=Coline|last6=Achten|first6=Wouter M. J.|date=January 2020|title=Dockless E-Scooter: A Green Solution for Mobility? Comparative Case Study between Dockless E-Scooters, Displaced Transport, and Personal E-Scooters|url=https://www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/12/5/1803|journal=Sustainability|language=en|volume=12|issue=5|pages=1803|doi=10.3390/su12051803|via=}}</ref>, as well as the long-term financial viability of micromobility companies given minimal differences between product offerings and operating costs in the hundreds of millions of [[United States dollar|US dollars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citylab.com/transportation/2020/01/electric-scooter-industry-safety-design-micromobility/605179/|title=4 Predictions for the Electric Scooter Industry|last=Bliss|first=Laura|website=CityLab|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Classification ==\nWithin the [[Vehicle category|EU vehicle categorization]] micromobility vehicles fall under the L category, and are excluded from the M, N, O and higher categories.\n\nDevices that fall within the definition of micromobility are typically classified as bicycles and are permitted to use [[Cycling infrastructure|bicycle infrastructure]] such as protected bicycle lanes, cycle tracks, cycle highways, and off-street trails. Classification as bicycles also means that users of personal micromobility modes are not required to register them, pay [[Motor vehicle registration|vehicle registration]] fees, or maintain [[liability insurance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/carltonreid/2019/01/22/eu-electric-bike-riders-will-not-need-compulsory-insurance-decides-european-parliament/|title=EU Electric Bike Riders Will Not Need Compulsory Insurance Decides European Parliament|last=Reid|first=Carlton|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wsd-pfb-sparkinfluence.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/2020/03/E-Bike-Law-Primer-Jan-2020-2.pdf|title=E-Bike Law Primer|last=|first=|date=April 2018|website=People for Bikes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Top 10 United States cities for micromobility potential==\nAccording to [[INRIX]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/12/breaking-news/study-ranks-honolulu-tops-in-micromobility-potential/| title=Study ranks Honolulu tops in micromobility potential| last=Wu| first=Nina| work=[[Star-Advertiser]]| location=[[Honolulu]]| date=2019-09-12| access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://inrix.com/press-releases/micromobility-study-us-2019/| title=Shared Bikes and Scooters Could Replace Nearly 50 Percent of Downtown Vehicle Trips: New INRIX Research ranks the top U.S., U.K. and German cities where micromobility has the most potential| work=[[INRIX]]| location=[[Kirkland, Washington]] |date=2019-09-09| access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> the following United States cities had the highest micromobility potential in 2019: \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Rank!!City\n|-\n| 1 ||  [[Honolulu]]\n|-\n| 2 ||  [[New Orleans]]\n|-\n| 3 ||  [[Nashville]]\n|-\n| 4 ||  [[Chicago]]\n|-\n| 5 ||  [[Charlotte]]\n|-\n| 6 ||  [[New York City]]\n|-\n| 7 ||  [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n|-\n| 8 ||  [[Pittsburgh]]\n|-\n| 9 ||  [[Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 10 ||  [[San Francisco]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Modes of Public Transport}}\n\n{{transport-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Bicycle sharing]]\n[[Category:Scooter sharing]]\n[[Category:Sharing economy]]\n", "name_user": "7&6=thirteen", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikify", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micromobility"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Portsmouth", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese\n| name              = Portsmouth\n| latin             = Dioecesis Portus Magni\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language -->\n| image             = Coat of arms of Philip Egan.svg\n| image_size        = frameless\n| image_alt         =\n| caption           = Current Bishop of Portsmouth \u2013 Coat of Arms\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[England]], <br/>[[Bailiwick of Guernsey]], <br/>[[Bailiwick of Jersey]]\n| territory         = [[Hampshire]], the [[Isle of Wight]], the [[Channel Islands]] and parts of [[Berkshire]], [[Dorset]] and [[Oxfordshire]]\n| province          = [[Province of Southwark|Southwark]]\n| metropolitan      = Southwark\n| archdeaconries    =\n| deaneries         = 24 (Pastoral Areas)\n| subdivisions      =\n| coordinates       = {{coord|50.799|-1.091|region:GB-HAM_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 6,339<!-- Area in square kilometres, automatically converted -->\n| area_sqmi         = <!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 2,563,000\n| population_as_of  = 2013\n| catholics         = 195,000\n| catholics_percent = 7.6\n| parishes          = 90\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 77<!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| sui_iuris_church  = [[Latin Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 19 May 1882\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of St John the Evangelist, Portsmouth|Portsmouth Cathedral]]\n| cocathedral       =\n| patron            = [[Edmund of Abingdon|St. Edmund of Abingdon]] and [[Immaculate Conception|The Immaculate Conception]]<!-- Patron saint(s) of the diocese (or archdiocese) -->\n| patron_title      = <!-- Use to override the default label \"Patron saint\" -->\n| priests           = 128<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| patriarch         =\n| major_archbishop  =\n| bishop            = [[Philip Egan]]\n| bishop_title      = <!-- Type of ordinary: i.e. Bishop or Archbishop. Default is Bishop -->\n| metro_archbishop  = [[John Wilson (bishop)|John Wilson]]\n| coadjutor         =\n| suffragans        = <!-- List most senior first (usually reckoned by date of consecration); use | suffragan = for one-->\n| auxiliary_bishops = <!-- List most senior first (usually reckoned by date of consecration) -->\n| apostolic_admin   =\n| vicar_general     =\n| episcopal_vicar   =\n| archdeacons       = <!-- List most senior first (usually reckoned by date of first collation); use | archdeacon = for one-->\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Crispian Hollis]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Province of Southwark.png\n| map_alt           =\n| map_caption       = The diocese within the Province of Southwark. <br/>The [[Channel Islands]] are not shown.\n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.portsmouthdiocese.org.uk/ portsmouthdiocese.org.uk]\n| footnotes         =\n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Portsmouth''' is a [[Latin Church]] [[Roman Catholic]] [[diocese]] that covers the [[Channel Islands]] as well as parts of [[England]] ([[Hampshire]], the [[Isle of Wight]] and parts of [[Berkshire]], [[Dorset]] and [[Oxfordshire]]). The episcopal see is the [[Cathedral of St John the Evangelist, Portsmouth|Portsmouth Cathedral]] and is headed by the [[Bishop of Portsmouth (Catholic)|Bishop of Portsmouth]]. The diocese is part of the metropolitan [[Province of Southwark]], which covers all of the far [[South of England]] as well as the Channel Islands.\n\n==Location==\nThe Diocese of Portsmouth, situated centrally within the [[Archdiocese of Southwark|Metropolitan Province of Southwark]], extending as far as [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire|Abingdon]] in the North; and down to and including the [[Channel Islands]] in the South, and roughly from Liphook in the East to [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]] in the West. The diocese adjoins the dioceses of [[Archdiocese of Birmingham|Birmingham]] and [[Diocese of Northampton|Northampton]] to the North, the [[Diocese of Arundel and Brighton|diocese of Arundel & Brighton]] to the East and the dioceses of [[Diocese of Plymouth|Plymouth]] and [[Diocese of Clifton|Clifton]] to the West. It officially comprises the counties of [[Hampshire]], Berkshire (south of the Thames), [[Oxfordshire]] (south of the Thames), [[Dorset]] (the Bournemouth area), the [[Isle of Wight]] and the Channel Islands.\n\nThe area of the Diocese of Portsmouth is 6,339&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (2,447sq Miles) with a total population (2001 census) of 2,960,077. Its estimated Catholic population (2004) is 167,000. There are 112 parishes (2005) and 128 incardinated priests, with a further 86 from religious orders, congregations & societies. There are also 31 permanent deacons serving in the parishes plus 101 professed, non-priest religious and 255 professed women religious. Education comprises 48 primary/middle/ecumenical schools (aided and grant maintained), 8 secondary and 24 independent schools.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Portsmouthcatholiccathedral.jpg|thumb|St John's Cathedral, Portsmouth|alt=]]\nBy a Papal Brief dated 19 May 1882, [[Pope Leo XIII]] created the Diocese of Portsmouth. It was formed out of the western portion of the Diocese of Southwark, as constituted at the re-establishment of the hierarchy in 1850.<ref name=king>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/12296a.htm King, John Henry. \"Diocese of Portsmouth.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 12. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 31 January 2020{{PD-notice}}</ref> The Southwark diocese had become too large for one bishop, extending as it did from London to [[Bournemouth]] and from the outskirts of [[Oxford]] to [[Dover]] and including the Channel Islands.\n\nThe new diocese comprised the counties of [[Hampshire]], the [[Isle of Wight]], Berkshire, and the [[Channel Islands]]. It was thus almost co-terminous with the limits of the (Anglican) [[Diocese of Winchester]]. The obvious place for the cathedral and curia of the new diocese was Winchester. The [[Ecclesiastical Titles Act]] forbade a Catholic diocese to have the same name as an [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] see. It would appear that the original intention was to fix the see at [[Southampton]], with [[St Joseph Church, Southampton|St Joseph Church]] in Bugle Street as the pro-cathedral. The construction of a large parish church in the centre of [[Portsmouth]] had begun, and it was decided to make it the future cathedral of the diocese.<ref name=hist>{{Cite web|url = http://www.catholicassociation.co.uk/groups/porthist.shtml|title = History of Portsmouth Diocese|accessdate = 13 December 2014|website = [[Catholic Association Pilgrimage]]|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140416210531/http://www.catholicassociation.co.uk/groups/porthist.shtml|archivedate = 16 April 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBishop Vertue was succeeded by his vicar-general [[John Cahill (bishop)|John Cahill]]. During Cahill's tenure a number of religious orders established houses in the diocese. In 1901 Benedictines from [[Solesmes Abbey]] settled on the [[Appuldurcombe House|Isle of Wight]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140505212939/http://www.iwcp.co.uk/news/wight-living/tragedy-scandal-and-wealth-the-story-of-one-great-house-56221.aspx Medland, John. \"Tragedy, scandal and wealth \u2013 the story of one great house\",''Isle of Wight County Press'', 11 April 2014]</ref> Benedictine [[nun]]<nowiki/>s established [[St Cecilia's Abbey, Ryde]]. Benedictine monks from the monastery of St. Edmund's, in Douai, France, came to [[Upper Woolhampton]] and founded [[Douai Abbey]] in 1903 when the community left France as a result of anti-clerical legislation.\n\n==Bishops==\n{{Main|Bishop of Portsmouth (Catholic)}}\n\nDr. [[John Vertue]] (1826\u20131900) was appointed the first bishop of the new diocese. He was consecrated by [[Henry Edward Manning|Cardinal Manning]] on 25 July 1882 and on 10 August of that year opened the [[Cathedral of St John the Evangelist, Portsmouth|Cathedral of St John the Evangelist at Portsmouth]]. When the new bishop took possession of his see, he had about seventy priests and forty missions.<ref name=king/>\n\nSince 1900 the diocese has had seven bishops: [[John Baptist Cahill|John Cahill]], 1900\u20131910; [[William Cotter (bishop)|William Cotter]] (who came from Cloyne in Co. Cork), 1910\u20131940; [[John King (bishop)|John Henry King]] (who was given the personal title of archbishop in 1954), 1941\u20131965; [[Derek Worlock]] (translated to [[Archdiocese of Liverpool|Liverpool]] as Archbishop 7 February 1976), 1965\u20131976; [[Anthony Emery (bishop)|Anthony Emery]], 1976\u20131988; [[Crispian Hollis]], 1988\u20132012;<ref name=hist/> [[ Philip Egan]], 2012-.\n\n===Current Bishop===\n{{Main|Philip Egan}}\n\nOn 11 July 2012, Bishop Egan's appointment as the Eighth Bishop of Portsmouth was announced in an official press release from the [[Vatican Information Service]] (VIS), an arm of the [[Holy See Press Office]]. At the time of his appointment Bishop Egan was serving as the [[Vicar General]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Shrewsbury|Diocese of Shrewsbury]].<ref name=shrews>[http://www.dioceseofshrewsbury.org/news/press-releases/pope-appoints-senior-cheshire-priest-as-bishop-of-portsmouth Pope Benedict XVI appoints Senior Cheshire Priest as Bishop of Portsmouth] from [[Diocese of Shrewsbury]], retrieved 13 December 2014</ref> Bishop Egan's Episcopal Ordination took place at St John\u2019s Cathedral, Portsmouth, on Monday 24 September 2012, the Feast of [[Our Lady of Walsingham]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-19691714 Fr Philip Egan ordained as Bishop of Portsmouth] from ''[[BBC News]]'', retrieved 13 December 2014</ref> \n\nBishop Egan was born on 14 November 1955 in [[Altrincham, England|Altrincham]], a suburb of [[Manchester, England|Manchester]]. After classical studies locally at [[St. Ambrose College]] and at [[King's College London]], he completed training for the priesthood at [[Allen Hall Seminary|Allen Hall]], [[Westminster]], and at the [[Venerable English College]] in Rome. On 4 August 1984, he was ordained to the priesthood for the Diocese of Shrewsbury. From 1984 to 1988, Egan served as parochial vicar at St. Anthony's, Woodehouse Park, Manchester. From 1988 to 1991, he served as an assistant chaplain at the [[University of Cambridge]]. From 1991 to 1994, he served as parish vicar and chaplain at Arrowe Park Hospital on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]]. From 1994 to 1995, he completed theological studies at [[Boston College]] in the United States, going on to serve, until 2007, as a Professor of [[Fundamental Theology]] and Dean of Studies at [[Oscott College]] seminary in [[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]]. In 2007\u20132008, also in Boston he attended [[Bernard Lonergan|Lonergan]] post-doctoral fellowship Studies. In 2008, Egan became parish priest of [[Blessed Virgin Mary (Roman Catholic)|Our Lady]] and [[St Christopher]]'s in [[Stockport, England|Stockport]]. In 2010, he was named to his previous post as Vicar General of the Diocese of Shrewsbury.\n\n===Emeritus Bishop===\n{{Main|Crispian Hollis}}\nThe [[Right Reverend]] Roger Francis Crispian Hollis, [[bishop emeritus]] of Portsmouth, was educated at [[Stonyhurst College]] and ordained on 11 July 1965.\n\nHe was installed as bishop of Portsmouth on 27 January 1989. He had been chairman of the Catholic Media Trust and chairman of the Bishops' Committee for Europe. He is a member of the Pontifical Council for Social Communications in the Vatican. He is the chairman of the Bishops' Conference Department of Mission and Unity, representative for the Bishops' Conference of the Churches Together in Britain and Ireland and a member of IARCCUM (International Anglican Roman Catholic Committee for Unity and Mission).\n\nHe reached the standard retirement age of 75 in November 2011.\n\nOn Tuesday, 11 July 2012, the acceptance of his resignation was announced in an official press release from the [[Vatican Information Service]] (VIS), an arm of the [[Holy See Press Office]].<ref name=shrews/>\n\n===Coadjutor Bishop===\n*[[Thomas Holland (bishop)|Thomas Holland]] (1960-1964), did not succeed to see; appointed Bishop of Salford\n\n===Auxiliary Bishops===\n*[[John Cahill (bishop)|John Baptist Cahill]] (1900-1904), appointed Bishop here\n*[[William Cotter (bishop)|William Timothy Cotter]] (1905-1910), appointed Bishop here\n*[[John King (bishop of Portsmouth)|John Henry King]] (1938-1941), appointed Bishop here\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n*[[Peter John Haworth Doyle]], appointed Bishop of Northampton in 2005\n*David Keane, appointed Bishop of Limerick, Ireland in 1923\n*[[Declan Ronan Lang]], appointed Bishop of Clifton in 2001\n*[[Cormac Murphy-O\u2019Connor]], appointed Bishop of Arundel and Brighton in 1977; future Cardinal\n\n==Other Notables of Diocese==\n'''Vicars General'''\n\nRev Canon Michael Dennehy VG\n\nRev Canon Paul Townsend VG (also Vicar for Clergy)\n\n'''Moderator for the Curia'''\n\nRev Canon Michael Dennehy VG\n\n'''Episcopal Vicar for Vocation'''\n\nRev Canon Gerard Flynn EpV\n\n'''Episcopal Vicar for Education'''\n\nRev Fr PJ Smith EpV (Also Dean of the Cathedral)\n\n'''Episcopal Vicar for Evangelisation'''\n\nRev Mark Hogan EpV\n\n'''Judicial Vicar'''\n\nRev Simon Thompson JCL JV\n\n'''Chancellor for the Diocese'''\n\nRev Stephen Restori\n\n==Pastoral Areas==\n\nFollowing a long period of consultation, the Diocese's new pastoral areas were launched at the time of [[Pentecost]] in 2006, with the aim to eventually turning them into parishes in the future. There were originally 24 pastoral areas. There are now 22. Deaneries were re-introduced in September 2014.\n\nThe Pastoral Areas with their respective parishes are, as of September 2014:\n\n* Deanery 1\n** New Forest: [[Brockenhurst]]  \u2013  [[Lymington]]  \u2013  [[Milford on Sea]]  \u2013  [[New Milton]]   \u2013  [[Totton]]  \u2013  Waterside  \u2013  [[Lyndhurst, Hampshire|Lyndhurst]]\n** Avon Stour: Bournemouth Our Lady Queen of Peace & Blessed Margaret Pole  \u2013  St Thomas More  \u2013 Christchurch  \u2013  Fordingbridge  \u2013  Highcliffe  \u2013  Ringwood\n** Bournemouth: Annunciation & St Edmund Campion  \u2013  [[Corpus Christi Church, Boscombe|Corpus Christi]]  \u2013  Our Lady Immaculate  \u2013 Sacred Heart\n* Deanery 2\n** Bailiwick of [[Guernsey]]: [[Alderney]]  \u2013  Guernsey\n** [[Jersey]]\n* Deanery 3\n** [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]]: English Martyrs  \u2013  St James & St William  \u2013  St Joseph  \u2013  Christ the King  \u2013  Our Lady of Peace & Blessed Dominic Barberi     \u2013  Woodley\n** Great Park: [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]]  \u2013  [[Maidenhead]] St Edmund Campion  \u2013  Maidenhead St Joseph  \u2013  Windsor  \u2013  [[Twyford, Berkshire|Twyford]]\n** South Berkshire: [[Bracknell]]: St Joseph and St Margaret Clitherow  \u2013  Crowthorne & Sandhurst  \u2013  [[Wokingham]]\n* Deanery 4\n** Petersfield: Bordon  \u2013  Grayshott  \u2013   Liphook  \u2013  [[Petersfield, Hampshire|Petersfield]]\n** Hampshire Downs: [[St Peter's Church, Winchester]]; St Stephen's Church, [[Olivers Battery]]; St Gregory the Great, Alresford; St Thomas More, Stockbridge; \u2013 [[Alton, Hampshire|Alton]]: St Mary's, Alton.\n** St Swithun Wells parish (formerly Three Rivers Pastoral Area, covering the former parishes of Bishop\u2019s Waltham  \u2013   Chandlers Ford  \u2013   [[Eastleigh]]  \u2013  [[Romsey]])\n* Deanery 5\n** Portsmouth: Portsmouth Cathedral  \u2013  Corpus Christi with St Joseph   \u2013  Our Lady & St Swithun  \u2013  St Colman with St Paul\n** Havant: [[Havant]]  \u2013  [[Hayling Island]]  \u2013  [[Horndean]]  \u2013  Leigh Park  \u2013  [[Waterlooville]]\n** Isle of Wight: [[Cowes]]  \u2013  [[East Cowes]]  \u2013  [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]]  [[Saint Thomas of Canterbury church, Newport, Isle of Wight|St Thomas of Canterbury]] \u2013  [[Ryde]]  \u2013  South Wight  \u2013  Totland Bay\n** Our Lady, Star of the Sea, Fareham and Gosport parish (formerly Solent Pastoral Area, covering the former parishes of [[Fareham]] \u2013 [[Portchester]]  \u2013  [[Gosport]]  \u2013  [[Lee-on-the-Solent]] with Stubbington  \u2013  Park Gate)\n* Deanery 6\n** Thames Isis: Abingdon  \u2013  [[Didcot]]  \u2013  East Hendred  \u2013  North Hinksey  \u2013  Wallingford\n** West Berkshire: [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]] St Francis de Sales  \u2013  Newbury St Joseph  \u2013  [[Thatcham]]  \u2013  Woolhampton\n** North Downs: Buckland & Faringdon  \u2013  Lambourn & [[Hungerford]]  \u2013  [[Wantage]]\n* Deanery 7\n** North East Hampshire: [[Aldershot]]  [[St Joseph's Church, Aldershot|St Joseph's]]\u2013  Fleet and Church Crookham  \u2013  [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]] Our Lady Help of Christians  \u2013  Farnborough Our Lady & St Dominic  \u2013  Hartley Wintney  \u2013  [[Yateley]]\n** North West Hampshire: Andover & Whitchurch  \u2013  [[Basingstoke]] Holy Ghost  \u2013  Basingstoke St Joseph  \u2013  Hook  \u2013  Tadley & Kingsclere  \u2013  [[Whitchurch, Hampshire|Whitchurch]]\n* Deanery 8\n** Southampton East: Hedge End  \u2013  [[Netley]]  \u2013  Southampton: Christ the King & St Colman  \u2013  Immaculate Conception  \u2013 St Patrick\n** Southampton Central and West: Holy Family  \u2013  St Boniface  \u2013  [[St Joseph Church, Southampton|St Joseph]] and [[St Edmund Church, Southampton|St Edmund]]  \u2013  St Vincent de Paul\n\n==Deaneries==\nDeaneries used to be used in the Diocese of Portsmouth, until pastoral areas were created to replace them. In 2005, they originally were: Portsmouth, Aldershot, Alton, Basingstoke, Bournemouth, Fareham, Havant, New Forest, Southampton, Winchester, North East Berks, South Berks, Kennet Valley, Vale of the White Horse, Reading, Isle of Wight, Guernsey and Jersey.\n\n==Pilgrimage==\nThe Portsmouth Diocese is part of the [[Catholic Association Pilgrimage]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{catholic|title=Diocese of Portsmouth}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1913CatholicEnc|Diocese of Portsmouth}}\n*[http://www.portsmouthdiocese.org.uk/ Official site of the Diocese]\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dprts.html The Diocese of Portsmouth at the site www.catholic-hierarchy.org]\n\n{{Roman Catholic dioceses in England and Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Portsmouth|Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1882|Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century|Portsmouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese\n| name              = Portsmouth\n| latin             = Dioecesis Portus Magni\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language -->\n| image             = Coat of arms of Philip Egan.svg\n| image_size        = frameless\n| image_alt         =\n| caption           = Current Bishop of Portsmouth \u2013 Coat of Arms\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[England]], <br/>[[Bailiwick of Guernsey]], <br/>[[Bailiwick of Jersey]]\n| territory         = [[Hampshire]], the [[Isle of Wight]], the [[Channel Islands]] and parts of [[Berkshire]], [[Dorset]] and [[Oxfordshire]]\n| province          = [[Province of Southwark|Southwark]]\n| metropolitan      = Southwark\n| archdeaconries    =\n| deaneries         = 24 (Pastoral Areas)\n| subdivisions      =\n| coordinates       = {{coord|50.799|-1.091|region:GB-HAM_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 6,339<!-- Area in square kilometres, automatically converted -->\n| area_sqmi         = <!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 2,563,000\n| population_as_of  = 2013\n| catholics         = 195,000\n| catholics_percent = 7.6\n| parishes          = 90\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 77<!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| sui_iuris_church  = [[Latin Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 19 May 1882\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of St John the Evangelist, Portsmouth|Portsmouth Cathedral]]\n| cocathedral       =\n| patron            = [[Edmund of Abingdon|St. Edmund of Abingdon]] and [[Immaculate Conception|The Immaculate Conception]]<!-- Patron saint(s) of the diocese (or archdiocese) -->\n| patron_title      = <!-- Use to override the default label \"Patron saint\" -->\n| priests           = 128<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| patriarch         =\n| major_archbishop  =\n| bishop            = [[Philip Egan]]\n| bishop_title      = <!-- Type of ordinary: i.e. Bishop or Archbishop. Default is Bishop -->\n| metro_archbishop  = [[John Wilson (bishop)|John Wilson]]\n| coadjutor         =\n| suffragans        = <!-- List most senior first (usually reckoned by date of consecration); use | suffragan = for one-->\n| auxiliary_bishops = <!-- List most senior first (usually reckoned by date of consecration) -->\n| apostolic_admin   =\n| vicar_general     =\n| episcopal_vicar   =\n| archdeacons       = <!-- List most senior first (usually reckoned by date of first collation); use | archdeacon = for one-->\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Crispian Hollis]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Province of Southwark.png\n| map_alt           =\n| map_caption       = The diocese within the Province of Southwark. <br/>The [[Channel Islands]] are not shown.\n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.portsmouthdiocese.org.uk/ portsmouthdiocese.org.uk]\n| footnotes         =\n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Portsmouth''' is a [[Latin Church]] [[Roman Catholic]] [[diocese]] that covers the [[Channel Islands]] as well as parts of [[England]] ([[Hampshire]], the [[Isle of Wight]] and parts of [[Berkshire]], [[Dorset]] and [[Oxfordshire]]). The episcopal see is the [[Cathedral of St John the Evangelist, Portsmouth|Portsmouth Cathedral]] and is headed by the [[Bishop of Portsmouth (Catholic)|Bishop of Portsmouth]]. The diocese is part of the metropolitan [[Province of Southwark]], which covers all of the far [[South of England]] as well as the Channel Islands.\n\n==Location==\nThe Diocese of Portsmouth, situated centrally within the [[Archdiocese of Southwark|Metropolitan Province of Southwark]], extending as far as [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire|Abingdon]] in the North; and down to and including the [[Channel Islands]] in the South, and roughly from Liphook in the East to [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]] in the West. The diocese adjoins the dioceses of [[Archdiocese of Birmingham|Birmingham]] and [[Diocese of Northampton|Northampton]] to the North, the [[Diocese of Arundel and Brighton|diocese of Arundel & Brighton]] to the East and the dioceses of [[Diocese of Plymouth|Plymouth]] and [[Diocese of Clifton|Clifton]] to the West. It officially comprises the counties of [[Hampshire]], Berkshire (south of the Thames), [[Oxfordshire]] (south of the Thames), [[Dorset]] (the Bournemouth area), the [[Isle of Wight]] and the Channel Islands.\n\nThe area of the Diocese of Portsmouth is 6,339&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (2,447sq Miles) with a total population (2001 census) of 2,960,077. Its estimated Catholic population (2004) is 167,000. There are 112 parishes (2005) and 128 incardinated priests, with a further 86 from religious orders, congregations & societies. There are also 31 permanent deacons serving in the parishes plus 101 professed, non-priest religious and 255 professed women religious. Education comprises 48 primary/middle/ecumenical schools (aided and grant maintained), 8 secondary and 24 independent schools.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Portsmouthcatholiccathedral.jpg|thumb|St John's Cathedral, Portsmouth|alt=]]\nBy a Papal Brief dated 19 May 1882, [[Pope Leo XIII]] created the Diocese of Portsmouth. It was formed out of the western portion of the Diocese of Southwark, as constituted at the re-establishment of the hierarchy in 1850.<ref name=king>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/12296a.htm King, John Henry. \"Diocese of Portsmouth.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 12. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 31 January 2020{{PD-notice}}</ref> The Southwark diocese had become too large for one bishop, extending as it did from London to [[Bournemouth]] and from the outskirts of [[Oxford]] to [[Dover]] and including the Channel Islands.\n\nThe new diocese comprised the counties of [[Hampshire]], the [[Isle of Wight]], Berkshire, and the [[Channel Islands]]. It was thus almost co-terminous with the limits of the (Anglican) [[Diocese of Winchester]]. The obvious place for the cathedral and curia of the new diocese was Winchester. The [[Ecclesiastical Titles Act]] forbade a Catholic diocese to have the same name as an [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] see. It would appear that the original intention was to fix the see at [[Southampton]], with [[St Joseph Church, Southampton|St Joseph Church]] in Bugle Street as the pro-cathedral. The construction of a large parish church in the centre of [[Portsmouth]] had begun, and it was decided to make it the future cathedral of the diocese.<ref name=hist>{{Cite web|url = http://www.catholicassociation.co.uk/groups/porthist.shtml|title = History of Portsmouth Diocese|accessdate = 13 December 2014|website = [[Catholic Association Pilgrimage]]|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140416210531/http://www.catholicassociation.co.uk/groups/porthist.shtml|archivedate = 16 April 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBishop Vertue was succeeded by his vicar-general [[John Cahill (bishop)|John Cahill]]. During Cahill's tenure a number of religious orders established houses in the diocese. In 1901 Benedictines from [[Solesmes Abbey]] settled on the [[Appuldurcombe House|Isle of Wight]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140505212939/http://www.iwcp.co.uk/news/wight-living/tragedy-scandal-and-wealth-the-story-of-one-great-house-56221.aspx Medland, John. \"Tragedy, scandal and wealth \u2013 the story of one great house\",''Isle of Wight County Press'', 11 April 2014]</ref> Benedictine [[nun]]<nowiki/>s established [[St Cecilia's Abbey, Ryde]]. Benedictine monks from the monastery of St. Edmund's, in Douai, France, came to [[Upper Woolhampton]] and founded [[Douai Abbey]] in 1903 when the community left France as a result of anti-clerical legislation.\n\n==Bishops==\n{{Main|Bishop of Portsmouth (Catholic)}}\n\nDr. [[John Vertue]] (1826\u20131900) was appointed the first bishop of the new diocese. He was consecrated by [[Henry Edward Manning|Cardinal Manning]] on 25 July 1882 and on 10 August of that year opened the [[Cathedral of St John the Evangelist, Portsmouth|Cathedral of St John the Evangelist at Portsmouth]]. When the new bishop took possession of his see, he had about seventy priests and forty missions.<ref name=king/>\n\nSince 1900 the diocese has had seven bishops: [[John Baptist Cahill|John Cahill]], 1900\u20131910; [[William Cotter (bishop)|William Cotter]] (who came from Cloyne in Co. Cork), 1910\u20131940; [[John King (bishop)|John Henry King]] (who was given the personal title of archbishop in 1954), 1941\u20131965; [[Derek Worlock]] (translated to [[Archdiocese of Liverpool|Liverpool]] as Archbishop 7 February 1976), 1965\u20131976; [[Anthony Emery (bishop)|Anthony Emery]], 1976\u20131988; [[Crispian Hollis]], 1988\u20132012;<ref name=hist/> [[ Philip Egan]], 2012-.\n\n===Current Bishop===\n{{Main|Philip Egan}}\n\nOn Tuesday, 11 July 2012, Bishop Egan's appointment as the Eighth Bishop of Portsmouth was announced in an official press release from the [[Vatican Information Service]] (VIS), an arm of the [[Holy See Press Office]]. At the time of his appointment Bishop Egan was serving as the [[Vicar General]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Shrewsbury|Diocese of Shrewsbury]].<ref name=shrews>[http://www.dioceseofshrewsbury.org/news/press-releases/pope-appoints-senior-cheshire-priest-as-bishop-of-portsmouth Pope Benedict XVI appoints Senior Cheshire Priest as Bishop of Portsmouth] from [[Diocese of Shrewsbury]], retrieved 13 December 2014</ref> Bishop Egan's Episcopal Ordination took place at St John\u2019s Cathedral, Portsmouth on Monday 24 September 2012, the Feast of [[Our Lady of Walsingham]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-19691714 Fr Philip Egan ordained as Bishop of Portsmouth] from ''[[BBC News]]'', retrieved 13 December 2014</ref> \n\nBishop Egan was born on 14 November 1955, in [[Altrincham, England|Altrincham]], a suburb of [[Manchester, England|Manchester]]. After classical studies locally at [[St. Ambrose College]] and at [[King's College London]], he completed training for the priesthood at [[Allen Hall Seminary|Allen Hall]], [[Westminster]], and at the [[Venerable English College]] in Rome. On 4 August 1984, he was ordained to the priesthood for the Diocese of Shrewsbury. From 1984 to 1988, Egan served as parochial vicar at St. Anthony's, Woodehouse Park, Manchester. From 1988 to 1991, he served as an assistant chaplain at the [[University of Cambridge]]. From 1991 to 1994, he served as parish vicar and chaplain at Arrowe Park Hospital on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]]. From 1994 to 1995, he completed theological studies at [[Boston College]] in the United States, going on to serve, until 2007, as a Professor of [[Fundamental Theology]] and Dean of Studies at [[Oscott College]] seminary in [[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]]. In 2007\u20132008, also in Boston he attended [[Lonergan Post]] Doctoral [[Fellowship (medicine)|Fellowship]] Studies. In 2008, Egan became parish priest of [[Blessed Virgin Mary (Roman Catholic)|Our Lady]] and [[St Christopher]]'s in [[Stockport, England|Stockport]]. In 2010, he was named to his previous post as Vicar General of the Diocese of Shrewsbury.\n\n===Emeritus Bishop===\n{{Main|Crispian Hollis}}\nThe [[Right Reverend]] Roger Francis Crispian Hollis, [[bishop emeritus]] of Portsmouth, was educated at [[Stonyhurst College]] and ordained on 11 July 1965.\n\nHe was installed as bishop of Portsmouth on 27 January 1989. He had been chairman of the Catholic Media Trust and chairman of the Bishops' Committee for Europe. He is a member of the Pontifical Council for Social Communications in the Vatican. He is the chairman of the Bishops' Conference Department of Mission and Unity, representative for the Bishops' Conference of the Churches Together in Britain and Ireland and a member of IARCCUM (International Anglican Roman Catholic Committee for Unity and Mission).\n\nHe reached the standard retirement age of 75 in November 2011.\n\nOn Tuesday, 11 July 2012, the acceptance of his resignation was announced in an official press release from the [[Vatican Information Service]] (VIS), an arm of the [[Holy See Press Office]].<ref name=shrews/>\n\n===Coadjutor Bishop===\n*[[Thomas Holland (bishop)|Thomas Holland]] (1960-1964), did not succeed to see; appointed Bishop of Salford\n\n===Auxiliary Bishops===\n*[[John Cahill (bishop)|John Baptist Cahill]] (1900-1904), appointed Bishop here\n*[[William Cotter (bishop)|William Timothy Cotter]] (1905-1910), appointed Bishop here\n*[[John King (bishop of Portsmouth)|John Henry King]] (1938-1941), appointed Bishop here\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n*[[Peter John Haworth Doyle]], appointed Bishop of Northampton in 2005\n*David Keane, appointed Bishop of Limerick, Ireland in 1923\n*[[Declan Ronan Lang]], appointed Bishop of Clifton in 2001\n*[[Cormac Murphy-O\u2019Connor]], appointed Bishop of Arundel and Brighton in 1977; future Cardinal\n\n==Other Notables of Diocese==\n'''Vicars General'''\n\nRev Canon Michael Dennehy VG\n\nRev Canon Paul Townsend VG (also Vicar for Clergy)\n\n'''Moderator for the Curia'''\n\nRev Canon Michael Dennehy VG\n\n'''Episcopal Vicar for Vocation'''\n\nRev Canon Gerard Flynn EpV\n\n'''Episcopal Vicar for Education'''\n\nRev Fr PJ Smith EpV (Also Dean of the Cathedral)\n\n'''Episcopal Vicar for Evangelisation'''\n\nRev Mark Hogan EpV\n\n'''Judicial Vicar'''\n\nRev Simon Thompson JCL JV\n\n'''Chancellor for the Diocese'''\n\nRev Stephen Restori\n\n==Pastoral Areas==\n\nFollowing a long period of consultation, the Diocese's new pastoral areas were launched at the time of [[Pentecost]] in 2006, with the aim to eventually turning them into parishes in the future. There were originally 24 pastoral areas. There are now 22. Deaneries were re-introduced in September 2014.\n\nThe Pastoral Areas with their respective parishes are, as of September 2014:\n\n* Deanery 1\n** New Forest: [[Brockenhurst]]  \u2013  [[Lymington]]  \u2013  [[Milford on Sea]]  \u2013  [[New Milton]]   \u2013  [[Totton]]  \u2013  Waterside  \u2013  [[Lyndhurst, Hampshire|Lyndhurst]]\n** Avon Stour: Bournemouth Our Lady Queen of Peace & Blessed Margaret Pole  \u2013  St Thomas More  \u2013 Christchurch  \u2013  Fordingbridge  \u2013  Highcliffe  \u2013  Ringwood\n** Bournemouth: Annunciation & St Edmund Campion  \u2013  [[Corpus Christi Church, Boscombe|Corpus Christi]]  \u2013  Our Lady Immaculate  \u2013 Sacred Heart\n* Deanery 2\n** Bailiwick of [[Guernsey]]: [[Alderney]]  \u2013  Guernsey\n** [[Jersey]]\n* Deanery 3\n** [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]]: English Martyrs  \u2013  St James & St William  \u2013  St Joseph  \u2013  Christ the King  \u2013  Our Lady of Peace & Blessed Dominic Barberi     \u2013  Woodley\n** Great Park: [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]]  \u2013  [[Maidenhead]] St Edmund Campion  \u2013  Maidenhead St Joseph  \u2013  Windsor  \u2013  [[Twyford, Berkshire|Twyford]]\n** South Berkshire: [[Bracknell]]: St Joseph and St Margaret Clitherow  \u2013  Crowthorne & Sandhurst  \u2013  [[Wokingham]]\n* Deanery 4\n** Petersfield: Bordon  \u2013  Grayshott  \u2013   Liphook  \u2013  [[Petersfield, Hampshire|Petersfield]]\n** Hampshire Downs: [[St Peter's Church, Winchester]]; St Stephen's Church, [[Olivers Battery]]; St Gregory the Great, Alresford; St Thomas More, Stockbridge; \u2013 [[Alton, Hampshire|Alton]]: St Mary's, Alton.\n** St Swithun Wells parish (formerly Three Rivers Pastoral Area, covering the former parishes of Bishop\u2019s Waltham  \u2013   Chandlers Ford  \u2013   [[Eastleigh]]  \u2013  [[Romsey]])\n* Deanery 5\n** Portsmouth: Portsmouth Cathedral  \u2013  Corpus Christi with St Joseph   \u2013  Our Lady & St Swithun  \u2013  St Colman with St Paul\n** Havant: [[Havant]]  \u2013  [[Hayling Island]]  \u2013  [[Horndean]]  \u2013  Leigh Park  \u2013  [[Waterlooville]]\n** Isle of Wight: [[Cowes]]  \u2013  [[East Cowes]]  \u2013  [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]]  [[Saint Thomas of Canterbury church, Newport, Isle of Wight|St Thomas of Canterbury]] \u2013  [[Ryde]]  \u2013  South Wight  \u2013  Totland Bay\n** Our Lady, Star of the Sea, Fareham and Gosport parish (formerly Solent Pastoral Area, covering the former parishes of [[Fareham]] \u2013 [[Portchester]]  \u2013  [[Gosport]]  \u2013  [[Lee-on-the-Solent]] with Stubbington  \u2013  Park Gate)\n* Deanery 6\n** Thames Isis: Abingdon  \u2013  [[Didcot]]  \u2013  East Hendred  \u2013  North Hinksey  \u2013  Wallingford\n** West Berkshire: [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]] St Francis de Sales  \u2013  Newbury St Joseph  \u2013  [[Thatcham]]  \u2013  Woolhampton\n** North Downs: Buckland & Faringdon  \u2013  Lambourn & [[Hungerford]]  \u2013  [[Wantage]]\n* Deanery 7\n** North East Hampshire: [[Aldershot]]  [[St Joseph's Church, Aldershot|St Joseph's]]\u2013  Fleet and Church Crookham  \u2013  [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]] Our Lady Help of Christians  \u2013  Farnborough Our Lady & St Dominic  \u2013  Hartley Wintney  \u2013  [[Yateley]]\n** North West Hampshire: Andover & Whitchurch  \u2013  [[Basingstoke]] Holy Ghost  \u2013  Basingstoke St Joseph  \u2013  Hook  \u2013  Tadley & Kingsclere  \u2013  [[Whitchurch, Hampshire|Whitchurch]]\n* Deanery 8\n** Southampton East: Hedge End  \u2013  [[Netley]]  \u2013  Southampton: Christ the King & St Colman  \u2013  Immaculate Conception  \u2013 St Patrick\n** Southampton Central and West: Holy Family  \u2013  St Boniface  \u2013  [[St Joseph Church, Southampton|St Joseph]] and [[St Edmund Church, Southampton|St Edmund]]  \u2013  St Vincent de Paul\n\n==Deaneries==\nDeaneries used to be used in the Diocese of Portsmouth, until pastoral areas were created to replace them. In 2005, they originally were: Portsmouth, Aldershot, Alton, Basingstoke, Bournemouth, Fareham, Havant, New Forest, Southampton, Winchester, North East Berks, South Berks, Kennet Valley, Vale of the White Horse, Reading, Isle of Wight, Guernsey and Jersey.\n\n==Pilgrimage==\nThe Portsmouth Diocese is part of the [[Catholic Association Pilgrimage]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{catholic|title=Diocese of Portsmouth}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1913CatholicEnc|